Q2: Cluster Analysis(hierarchical)

Data1<-as.data.frame(scale(X))
dist<-dist(Data1, method="euclidian")
hc<-hclust(dist, method="single")
plot(hc, hang=-1)

As we can see from the dendogram, the distance between these two clusters which were cut is very small, and one single case (Rwanda) was separated from the others. I have tried to cut 4 clusters as I think the generalization is too much for the other countries.

plot(hc, hang=-1)
rect.hclust(hc, 4)

Again here is the same problem, therefore I want to have more general clusters which will group several countries.So I will exclude some countries which are too different from others maybe beacause of their social and economical factors, or these countries can be the richest or the poorest ones.

Data$Country[c(109,3,137,35,99,42,8,118,66,78,96,25,54,71,132,59,12)]

These are countries which do not let the model to comprise more general groups. I will exclude some of them from the data and again do clustering for the remaining countries.

Data2<-Data[-c(109,3,137,35,99,42,8,118,66,78,96,25,54,71,132,59,12),]
dist2<-dist(Data2[3:14], method="euclidian")
hc1<-hclust(dist2, method="single")
plot(hc1, hang=-1)

plot(hc1, hang=-1)
rect.hclust(hc1,3)

Now I’ve got results which are more favorable, as the distance between clusters is comparitevely high and clusters include many cases.

Data2$cl_membership<-cutree(hc1,k=3)

Based on the table we can name the clusters as follows: I would like to name the second group of countries as “innovation-driven economies” as they have higher values not only amlmost for all variables also the mena valuse for 11th and 12th variables(which are innovation factors) are very high compared with the first and third group, which means that these countries can be called also developed countries. The third group may include countries which are developing and they may be called “efficiency-driven economies” as they have especially higher values for the 5-10th variables which are called efficiency enhancers, and the first group may include underdeveloped and transition economies which can called “factor” driven. # K-means method.

To see how countries in 3 the clusters differ from each other, I have constructed boxplots.

boxplot(Data2$GDP~Data2$cl_membership)

As the boxplot shows the GDP of the first group countries is changing in a big range, however the median GDP for second group is higher than for the first and third clusters.

boxplot(Data2$Education.expenditures.2013~Data2$cl_membership)

Here we again can see that the second group expends more on education compared with others, so we can continue to name this group as the cluster of high developed countries. The 1st cluster includes transition economies like Russia and for example India as underdeveloped country, so for this group education expenditures varies from very to very high values, but for the 3rd group(developing countries) expenditures don’t vary too much.

boxplot(Data2$Market.Capitalization~Data2$cl_membership)

It is a well known fact that the market capitalization in high developed countries is very high while developing and underdeveloped countries mainly don’t have advanced financial markets.As we can see boxplot of the first group contains a lot of outliers, this is again because these countries have different level of progress and this group contains also countries which can soon transformed from underdeveloped to developing. And as can be seen, the third(developing countries) have higher market capitalization.

boxplot(Data2$Trade~Data2$cl_membership)

As we know, nowadayas the huge part of the world trade accounts for developed countries, and the boxplot again shows that the volumes of trades is a little bit higher for developed contries compared with developing and underdeveloped countries.

boxplot(Data2$Net.Export~Data2$cl_membership)

From the first view it can be seem strange that net export for the developed countries is lower than for developing ones, however this may be result of the fact that the data was given in absolute numbers and volumes of developed countries’ export and import are too high, so the difference(net export) may be lower.

To sum up, taking into account the concepts of The Global Competitiveness Report we made sure that developed countries are more innovative-driven and have very high macroeconomic and socioeconomic indicators while for underdeveloped countries these indicators vary in a high range and on average are lower, and for them the first importance is to satisfy basic requirements so these are mainly factor driven countries which are on the stage of developing main infrustructures and institutions. Developing countries are more efficiency driven and have comparitavely equal level of development.
